Need an easy basic concepts activity for speech therapy? Want a freebie?!🙋🏻‍♀️

Grab the pictured FREE one sheet basic concept visuals and pair it with your favorite toys! Im obsessed with this @learningresources surprise party set!  You can use it for targeting ALL the basic concepts and kids love the element of surprise! 

🎁spatial concepts: put the mini objects in different locations around the present boxes 
🎁qualitative concepts: make big and little stacks of boxes, talk about open vs closed boxes, sort by same and different colors 
🎁temporal concepts: put the animals in a line 
🎁quantitative concepts: draw two circles and practice all/none, more/less, etc. 

You can also work on describing attributes, answering wh- questions, following directions, colors, and more!🥳

I’ve always been obsessed with Osmo and am so excited to add this @playosmo coding starter kit to our collection!  This fun and interactive game is hands-on and requires children to use problem solving skills by moving physical blocks of code in front of them! 

As a mom of a kindergartner, I love Osmo’s positive approach to screen time that incorporates hands on play with technology! The Osmo reflector sees the child’s physical movements, making it interactive.

Thank you to @playosmo for gifting us this awesome game set! Have you tried Osmo? What’s your favorite @playosmo game?! #gifted #ad  #learningwellplayed #osmosocialclub

Obsessed with this @learningresources surprise picnic baskets toy 😍

Perfect for so many language targets!
💛spatial concepts: put the mini objects on, in, next to the baskets, etc. 
💚quantitative concepts: divide the baskets and objects between you and the child and practice more, less, one, many, etc. 
💙describing by attributes: colors, shapes, naming categories, etc. 
🤍following directions (Put the grapes in the green basket, then close the basket.)
🖤wh questions (What fruits do you see?)

Practice a variety of spatial concepts while moving the ghost around the @magnatiles house! 

👻Behind the door 
👻On top of the house 
👻Next to the house 
👻Under the purple roof 
👻In the house
👻Behind the house

🎃Practice describing (colors, shapes, size)
🎃Practice following multi-step directions (first put the ghost in front of the house, then put the ghost behind the house)
🎃Wind up the toy and practice core words (stop, go, more, help)

📚There are so many benefits of reading to little ones! A few benefits of reading to your baby are: 

💛Increased vocabulary exposure
💛Visual Stimulation (exposing to high contrast books with a variety of colors, shapes) 
💛Learning pre-literacy skills (holding a book, turning pages, etc)
💛Bonding with caregiver/parent

📋In a research study by Marshall et al, reading to babies daily was associated with higher language scores seen at as early as 9 months old. 

This study included infants as young as 2 months old and followed them until they were 12 months old. The results showed that when families read at least 7 books per week, infants scored higher in the areas of receptive, expressive, and combined language tests.

🎁spatial concepts: put the mini objects in different locations around the present boxes
